  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Promoting Tolerance in MENA</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">(USAID Middle East Regional (MER)):  In many contexts, violence and the incitement of violence targeting communities or individuals based on their identity as a member of a religious and ethnic minority population (REM), characterize atrocity crimes (including genocide, war crimes, crimes against humanity, and ethnic cleansing). Oftentimes, this type of violence and discrimination against particular REM populations also constitutes an early warning sign and risk factor for mass atrocities. This activity will reduce the risk of atrocities against religious and ethnic minorities in Libya, Yemen, Tunisia, and Morocco by improving atrocity recognition and communication, prevention, and response. MER programming will support the achievement of three objectives: 1) Conduct Atrocity Risk Assessment and Identify Early Warning and other Prevention and Response Mechanisms for at-risk REM Populations; 2) Pilot an Early Warning System based on Recommendations for at-risk REM populations; and 3) Support Additional Atrocity Prevention, Response, and Recovery Efforts for REM populations. The implementing partner will accomplish the first objective through country-specific research products with actionable recommendations analyzing atrocity risks, barriers to services, and existing approaches to atrocity early warning systems. This analysis will feed into the attainment of the second objective, which will pilot these recommendations in one or more countries. The activity will reach the third objective through capacity building for civil society and local government as well as rapid responses/small grants to enable recipients to respond quickly to unanticipated needs that arise among REM communities. Monitoring, preventing, and countering incitement to violence, particularly in societies divided along identity lines and in situations where tensions are high, can contribute to both prevention efforts and efforts to advance U.S. policies promoting pluralistic societies that respect fr</narrative>
  </description>
